    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Gummies for Men</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What vitamins do men need most?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin D (testosterone, immunity — 42% deficient), zinc (testosterone, prostate), magnesium (300+ enzymes, testosterone), B12 (energy, neurological), omega-3 (heart health — #1 male killer), and selenium (prostate antioxidant protection).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do men's multivitamins really support testosterone?</summary>
      <p>They optimize natural production by correcting deficiencies — not boost above physiological levels. Zinc supplementation in deficient men increased testosterone 93%. Vitamin D supplementation in deficient men increased it 25%. The key is correcting existing deficiencies.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do men's vitamins have less iron than women's?</summary>
      <p>Men do not lose blood through menstruation and need only 8mg iron daily (vs 18mg for premenopausal women). Excess iron causes organ damage (hemochromatosis). Most men's multivitamins contain zero iron. Only supplement iron if blood work shows low ferritin.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between men's and unisex multivitamins?</summary>
      <p>Men's formulas: zero iron, higher zinc and selenium (testosterone/prostate), higher B vitamins (energy), sometimes lycopene or saw palmetto. They exclude nutrients women need in higher amounts (iron, folate at pregnancy doses, calcium at osteoporosis doses).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>At what age should men start taking a multivitamin?</summary>
      <p>Any age if diet has gaps. In 20s-30s: zinc, magnesium, B vitamins for energy. In 40s: vitamin D, omega-3 as heart risk rises and testosterone declines. In 50s+: high-dose B12 (absorption declines), prostate nutrients (selenium, lycopene, zinc).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take a men's multivitamin with other supplements?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Calculate total daily intake to avoid exceeding upper limits. Common stacks: multi + creatine, multi + omega-3, multi + ashwagandha. Avoid doubling up on zinc (max 40mg/day), vitamin A (max 3,000mcg), or selenium (max 400mcg).</p>
    </details>

